./ftui-harness --test-mode animation --animation spinner --duration 2s --record spinner.gif

# Test under load (should degrade gracefully)
./ftui-harness --test-mode animation-stress --animations 10 --load-factor 5
# Assert: no dropped frames visible
# Assert: animations complete eventually

# Verify easing curves
cargo test animation::easing -- --nocapture
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Core animation types (Fade, Slide, Pulse)
- [ ] Composition (sequence, parallel, delay)
- [ ] Easing functions (ease_in, ease_out, ease_in_out)
- [ ] Integration with render budget (graceful degradation)
- [ ] Spinner/Progress widgets use animations
- [ ] Zero allocation during tick
- [ ] All tests pass","notes":"## Edge Case Handling

Animations must handle edge cases gracefully:

```rust
impl Fade {
    pub fn new(duration: Duration) -> Self {
        // Handle zero duration
        let duration = if duration.is_zero() {
            Duration::from_millis(1)  // Minimum 1ms
        } else {
            duration
        };
        Self { progress: 0.0, duration }
    }
}

impl Animation for Fade {
    fn tick(&mut self, dt: Duration) {
        // Clamp progress to [0, 1]
        let delta = dt.as_secs_f32() / self.duration.as_secs_f32();
        self.progress = (self.progress + delta).clamp(0.0, 1.0);
    }

    fn value(&self) -> f32 {
        self.progress  // Already clamped
    }
}

// Easing functions must handle edge cases
pub fn ease_in(t: f32) -> f32 {
    t.clamp(0.0, 1.0).powi(2)  // Clamp input
}
```

### Edge Cases to Test
- Zero duration animation
- Very long duration (hours)
- Negative dt (should not happen but handle gracefully)
- NaN/Infinity values
- Rapid tick calls (dt < 1ms)
- Animation tick after completion

